<workbook_page xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/" id="_u5_m01_confidence_interval_mean8">
<head>
<title>Confidence Intervals for the Population Mean (8 of 8)</title>
    <objref idref="explain_confidence_interval"/>
    <objref idref="find_confidence_intervals"/>
</head>
<body>
    
    
<section>
<title>Let's summarize</title>
<body>
<p><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170107-0500" comment="use bullets rather than asterisks"?>*<?oxy_comment_end?>
                    When the population is normal and/or the sample is large, a confidence interval
                    for unknown population mean μ when σ is known
                    is<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170129-0500" content=" "?>:</p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>x</m:mi>
<m:mo>¯</m:mo>
</m:mover>
<m:mo>±</m:mo>
<m:mi>z</m:mi>
<m:mo>∗</m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mi mathvariant="normal">σ</m:mi>
<m:msqrt>
<m:mi>n</m:mi>
</m:msqrt>
</m:mfrac>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>, where z* is 1.645 for 90% confidence, 2 for 95% confidence, and 2.576 for 99% confidence.</p>
<p>* There is a
                    trade<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170146-0500"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>off
                    between the level of confidence and the precision of the interval estimation.
                    The price we have to pay for more precision is sacrificing level of
                    confidence<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170159-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
<p>* The general form of confidence intervals is
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170210-0500"?>an
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>estimate +/-
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170300-0500"?>the
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>margin of error
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170304-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>m<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170306-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>.
                    In this case<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170309-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170316-0500"?>the <?oxy_insert_end?>estimate<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170319-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170320-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?><m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mover>
                                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                            </m:mover>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math> and <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>∗</m:mo>
                            <m:mfrac>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">σ</m:mi>
                                <m:msqrt>
                                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                                </m:msqrt>
                            </m:mfrac>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math>. The confidence interval is therefore centered at the estimate and its
                    width is exactly 2m.</p>
<p>* For a given level of confidence, the width of the interval depends on the sample size. We can therefore do a sample size calculation to figure out what sample size is needed in order to get a confidence interval with a desired margin of error m, and a certain level of confidence (assuming we have some flexibility with the sample size). To do the sample size calculation we use:</p>
<p>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:msup>
                                <m:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                    <m:mfrac>
                                        <m:mrow>
                                            <m:msup>
                                                <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                                                <m:mo>*</m:mo>
                                            </m:msup>
                                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">σ</m:mi>
                                        </m:mrow>
                                        <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                                    </m:mfrac>
                                </m:mfenced>
                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                            </m:msup>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170435-0500" content="."?></p>
<p> (and round <em>up</em> to the next
                    integer)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170438-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
<p>* When σ is unknown, we use the sample standard deviation, s, instead, but as a result
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170506-0500"?>we also
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>need to use a different set of confidence multipliers (t*)
                    associated with the t distribution. The interval is therefore</p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>x</m:mi>
<m:mo>¯</m:mo>
</m:mover>
<m:mo>±</m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mi>t</m:mi>
<m:mo>*</m:mo>
</m:msup>
<m:mo>∗</m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mi>s</m:mi>
<m:msqrt>
<m:mi>n</m:mi>
</m:msqrt>
</m:mfrac>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>
</p>
<p>* These new multipliers have the added complexity that they depend not only on the level of
                    confidence<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170520-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    but also on the sample size. Software is therefore very useful for calculating
                    confidence intervals in this case.</p>
<p>* For
                    <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170621-0500" comment="Should &quot;large&quot; be given a standard number definition? "?>large<?oxy_comment_end?>
                    values of n, the t*
                    multipliers<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170529-0500" content=","?>
                    are not that different from the z* multipliers, and therefore using the
                    interval<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T171143-0500"?>
                    formula<?oxy_insert_end?>:</p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>x</m:mi>
<m:mo>¯</m:mo>
</m:mover>
<m:mo>±</m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mi>z</m:mi>
<m:mo>∗</m:mo>
</m:msup>
<m:mo>∗</m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mi>s</m:mi>
<m:msqrt>
<m:mi>n</m:mi>
</m:msqrt>
</m:mfrac>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>
</p>
<p><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T171151-0500"?>for<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T171148-0500" content="to estimate"?>
                    μ when σ is unknown
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170836-0500"?>provides
                    <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170835-0500" content="is"?>
                    a pretty good
                    approximation<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101123T170544-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
<p> </p>
